She said at the museum in Nairobi has launched a programme on The people of Kenya to tell stories about Kenya’s heroes and heroines. 

“We unveiled all the heroes and heroines of our country from every community and sect. We are beginning to tell their stories, giving us a sense of pride, dignity and continuation of our journey. We must take pride from everything that has happened in our country, the good, the bad and the ugly, it’s all part of our history and we have to acknowledged, own and celebrate them in different ways,” she added. 

Ms Mohamed further assured Kenyans that her ministry will revamp all the historical sites that are in ruins to protect them against any threats including climate change. For instance at Fort Jesus, she said the government has built a seawall to protect the fort from being eroded by the sea. 



